# Test Approach

## Functional Over Implementation

Prioritize functional tests that assert observable behavior (output, UI, side effects). Avoid tests tied to internal implementation details.

### Assert behavior

- User-visible results: rendered text, roles, disabled state, callbacks fired
- Public outputs: return values, thrown errors, emitted events
- Integration outcomes: API calls, toasts, navigation

### Avoid implementation details

- Internal state, private functions, or module internals
- Static class names that are always present
- Exact call order unless order is the behavior under test
- Snapshot-only coverage with no behavioral assertion for logic-heavy code

- ✅ Good:

  ```tsx
  it('should disable button when "loading" is true', () => {
    render(<Button loading>Submit</Button>)
    expect(screen.getByRole('button', { name: 'Submit' })).toBeDisabled()
  })

  it('should return formatted price', () => {
    expect(formatPrice(1000)).toBe('R$ 1.000,00')
  })
  ```

- ❌ Bad:

  ```tsx
  it('should set internal loading flag', () => {
    const { result } = renderHook(() => useButtonState())
    act(() => result.current.setLoading(true))
    expect(result.current._internalLoading).toBe(true)
  })

  it('should call "useMemo" twice', () => {
    const spy = vi.spyOn(React, 'useMemo')
    render(<ExpensiveList items={items} />)
    expect(spy).toHaveBeenCalledTimes(2)
  })
  ```

## Base Props and Params

When multiple tests share the same component props or function arguments, extract reusable base constants. Override only what each test needs.

- ✅ Good:

  ```tsx
  const defaultProps = {
    label: 'Submit',
    onClick: vi.fn(),
    loading: false,
  }

  const renderButton = (props: Partial<typeof defaultProps> = {}) =>
    render(<Button {...defaultProps} {...props} />)

  it('should call "onClick" when clicked', async () => {
    const onClick = vi.fn()
    renderButton({ onClick })

    await userEvent.click(screen.getByRole('button', { name: 'Submit' }))
    expect(onClick).toHaveBeenCalledTimes(1)
  })
  ```

  ```typescript
  const defaultOptions = {
    dealId: '123',
    fieldName: 'objective' as const,
    initialContent: 'Initial content',
  }

  it('should initialize with default values', () => {
    const { result } = renderHook(() => useDebouncedObjectivesForm(defaultOptions))
    expect(result.current.getValues().dealId).toBe('123')
  })
  ```

- ❌ Bad:

  ```tsx
  it('should call onClick when clicked', async () => {
    const onClick = vi.fn()
    render(<Button label="Submit" onClick={onClick} loading={false} />)
    // repeated full props in every test
  })
  ```

Name constants `defaultProps`, `baseProps`, `defaultOptions`, or `baseParams` depending on context.

## Related Conventions

- Prefer `it.each` for similar cases — see [test-organization](test-organization.mdc)
- Prefer shared mocks from `@/mocks/` and `__mocks__` — see [test-mocks](test-mocks.mdc)
